## Distance
The driving distance from **Los Angeles to San Francisco is approximately 382-383 miles**, taking about **6-7 hours** on the I-5 highway if traveling non-stop. However, traffic (especially around LA and the Bay Area) can extend this time considerably.

## Best Route & Stops

While the I-5 is the fastest route, many travelers prefer the scenic **Pacific Coast Highway (Highway 1) or Highway 101**, which takes 3-4 days and offers incredible coastal views and attractions. Here are some recommended stops along the way:

**Popular stops on the scenic route include:**
- **Santa Barbara** - Beautiful coastal town with beaches and Spanish architecture
- **San Luis Obispo** - Charming Central Coast city
- **Hearst Castle** - Historic mansion near San Simeon
- **Big Sur** - Stunning coastal scenery and hiking opportunities
- **Monterey** - Coastal city with the famous Monterey Bay Aquarium
- **Carmel-by-the-Sea** - Picturesque seaside village
- **Santa Cruz** - Beach town with the famous boardwalk
- **Half Moon Bay** - Scenic coastal town (good for pumpkins in fall)

If you're looking for the quickest route, take I-5. If you have time and want to experience California's beautiful coastline, the Pacific Coast Highway is well worth the extra time!The capital of Australia is **Canberra**.

Canberra is located in the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and was purpose-built as the nation's capital city. It was chosen as a compromise between rivals Sydney and Melbourne, and was designed by American architects Walter Burley Griffin and Marion Mahoney Griffin. The city was founded in 1913 and officially inaugurated in 1927.
